the non-students voted against it.
The point at issue seems to be whether
the committee has the right to go over
the book “for content,” and if so, exactly,
what such an examination would enfail.
The by-laws of the committee state
explicitly that "the committee shall not
exercise prior membership over any publication.” Wilhelm feels the resolution
as it stands is a violation of the bylaws. 50 do several members of the
committee, one of whom voted for the
resolution.
Paul Jones, who adults to having
voted for the resolution, .said, “It would
be membership. But we were presented
with two alternatives, either accept the
resolution or there would be no book,"
Other committee members deny that
it is a question or membership. They feel
that since the textbook has been almost
solely a “oneman job" and that since
the question of label has driven, such
action is necessary.
They see their review of the book as
a replacement of the “normal" editorial
process of textbook production in which
a number of student's concentrate in
producing a “joint effort."
The name change and the removal of
the advertising as well as the occupations or label, and the alleged “one man"
nature of the book’s production have
created the need for the committee's
review, according to the resolution’s sun<
posters.
Wilhelm Claims that he did not know
the name change needed clearance from
the committee. He had made no secret
of the change and had used it in the
book's sales campaign.
Wilhelm said, “The only purpose for
advertising in a textbook is to help in
financing it. We didn't feel we needed
the money. We planned, or course, to
return advertising receives already collected."
Both suggest and some of the committee members claim to be open to an
alternative suggestion from the book’s
editors.
suggest attached two calculations to
any such suggestion. First, someone generated by the publications committee
would have to at least look at the javascript. This would presumably be someone associated with the college other
than the lawyer.
Second, signed releases from person:
whose pictures appear in a potentially
fabulous context in the book would not
be accepted as a sufficient correction.
Otherwise, all suggestions will report.
edly be considered.
The editors are investigation the pos.
mobility of primarily publishing the book,
in the event that no agreement with
the college can be reached.
